  "prompt": "Why sound waves cannot be polarized?",
  "response": "Sound waves cannot be polarized because they are longitudinal waves, unlike electromagnetic waves which are transverse waves. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Wave Nature Differences:\n- Sound waves are mechanical waves that propagate through compression and rarefaction of the medium\n- Particles in sound waves oscillate parallel to the direction of wave propagation\n- These longitudinal vibrations cannot be oriented in different planes\n\n2. Mechanical Wave Characteristics:\n- Sound waves require a medium to travel\n- Particle displacement occurs along the wave's propagation direction\n- No perpendicular oscillation occurs that would allow polarization\n\n3. Polarization Requirements:\n- Polarization requires waves to oscillate perpendicular to wave propagation\n- Electromagnetic waves (light) have transverse oscillations that can be aligned\n- Sound waves lack this transverse component\n\n4. Contrast with Electromagnetic Waves:\n- Light waves are transverse and can be polarized using filters\n- Sound waves cannot be similarly filtered or oriented\n\n5. Physical Limitation:\n- The fundamental nature of sound wave propagation prevents directional filtering\n- Longitudinal wave characteristics inherently resist polarization mechanisms\n\nThese fundamental differences in wave structure explain why sound waves cannot be polarized, unlike electromagnetic waves.",
